A D-dimer cutoff point of 1570 ng/ml showed a sensitivity of 95.7%, specificity of 29.3%, positive predictive value of 19% and negative predictive value of 97.5%, and was chosen as the optimal cutoff point for ruling out asymptomatic DVT. D-dimer levels over 1570 ng/mL were associated with higher incidence of asymptomatic DVT (crude OR: 9.1; CI 95% 1.1–70.1). D-dimer levels were categorized into three ranges: 1000–1800, 1801–2650 and >2650 ng/ml. When we compared the 3 groups, we found differences in the prevalence of DVT: 3.8%, 10.5% and 25.8% respectively (p = 0.003). D-dimer showed an acceptable discriminative capacity (area under the ROC curve 0.72, 95% CI 0.61–0.84) (Fig. 1
). The predicted and the observed DVT rate showed no significant differences (p = 0.807) (Table 3
).
